'''Sumiyoshi Matsuri''' (住吉祭) is a folk event in {{ill|Japan|ja|日本|12=draft|12=draft}} in which, on the day of {{ill|Kōshin|ja|庚申|12=draft|12=draft}}, deities and Buddhist figures are enshrined and the community remains awake throughout the night. It is also known as "Yoi Kōshin" or "Osaru-machi". Sumiyoshi Matsuri is typically held on a village-wide basis, and the gathering ({{ill|Kō|ja|講|12=draft|12=draft}}) is referred to as either '''Kōshin-kō''', '''Kōshin-e''', or "Ohimachi", among other names.
== Overview == [[File:Osaka-zu_byobu_Aranigono_oharae_shinji.jpg|alt=An Osaka folding screen from the Toyotomi period depicting the Aranigono purification ceremony at Sumiyoshi Taisha|thumb]] Sumiyoshi Matsuri centers on the annual festival ({{ill|Reitaisai|ja|例大祭|12=draft|12=draft}}) held on {{ill|July 31|ja|7月31日|12=draft|12=draft}} at {{ill|Sumiyoshi Taisha|ja|住吉大社|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Osaka City|ja|大阪市|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is one of the three major summer festivals in Osaka, along with the {{ill|Namikuni-dama Matsuri|ja|生國魂祭|12=draft|12=draft}} (at {{ill|Namikuni-dama Shrine|ja|生國魂神社|12=draft|12=draft}}) and the {{ill|Tenjin Matsuri|ja|天神祭|12=draft|12=draft}} (at {{ill|Osaka Tenmangu|ja|大阪天満宮|12=draft|12=draft}}). The term Sumiyoshi Matsuri may refer either specifically to a portion of the summer festival at Sumiyoshi Taisha or to the entire summer festival.
In a narrow sense, it denotes the sequence of events at Sumiyoshi Taisha comprising the evening festival held on {{ill|July 30|ja|7月30日|12=draft|12=draft}}, the summer purification ceremony ({{ill|Nageharae Shinji|ja|夏越祓神事|12=draft|12=draft}}), and the annual festival on {{ill|July 31|ja|7月31日|12=draft|12=draft}}. In a broader sense, it refers to the entire summer festival at Sumiyoshi Taisha that takes place from {{ill|Marine Day|ja|海の日|12=draft|12=draft}} in July until August 1. When locals refer to "Sumiyoshi Matsuri," they typically mean the Sumiyoshi Taisha summer festival events on July 31 and August 1 (i.e. the summer purification ceremony, the annual festival, and the mikoshi procession). (The Sumiyoshi Taisha official website explains the festival in the narrow sense.)
According to the ''{{ill|Sumiyoshi Taisha Shindai-ki|ja|住吉大社神代記|1=Sumiyoshi Taisha Shrine Chronicles|12=draft|12=draft}}'', the summer festival of Sumiyoshi Taisha (also known as "Oharae") was regularly held during the Nara period as the "Miharai" (purification ritual), also known as the "Minamatsuri", in June.
The current summer festival at Sumiyoshi Taisha begins on Marine Day in July with a mikoshi washing ceremony at {{ill|Sumiyoshi Park|ja|住吉公園|12=draft|12=draft}}. On {{ill|July 31|ja|7月31日|12=draft|12=draft}}, the summer purification ceremony (an event designated as an {{ill|Intangible Cultural Property|ja|無形文化財|12=draft|12=draft}}) and the annual festival at the main shrine are held, during which performances such as the Kumano Dance and the {{ill|Sumiyoshi Odori|ja|住吉踊り|12=draft|12=draft}} are presented. On {{ill|August 1|ja|8月1日|12=draft|12=draft}}, a mikoshi procession takes place. Since 2005, the mikoshi has once again been carried on foot.
== Schedule == * July (Marine Day): Mikoshi Washing Ceremony [https://www.youtube.com/embed/6mg4r8AJjSc?list=UUw08MwmQfjjZRABPX56t3aQ (video)] * July 30: Sumiyoshi Matsuri – Evening Festival (Yoi-matsuri) * July 31: Sumiyoshi Matsuri – Annual Festival (Reitaisai) [https://www.youtube.com/embed/73MndOUQhOA (video)] and Summer Purification Ceremony (Nageharae Shinji) * August 1: Mikoshi Procession [https://www.youtube.com/embed/B57Q6H3xj50?list=UUw08MwmQfjjZRABPX56t3aQ (video)], Tonmiya Festival, and Arawa (Aranigono) Purification Ceremony
== External Links == * [http://www.sumiyoshitaisha.net/events/special.html#anchor02 Special Festival – Sumiyoshi Matsuri] at {{ill|Sumiyoshi Taisha|ja|住吉大社|12=draft|12=draft}}
